<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-359-260  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 359 260.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lasers andamp; Optronics  April 1990 v9 n4 p23(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>On high-tech export, Dod and commerce sing different tunes.andO;(Department of Defense)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Morrison, David C.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Plans by telephone companies and the fiber optics industry tocreate a $500 million fiber optic telecommunications line fromWestern Europe to Japan is receiving resistance from theDepartment of Defense (DOD) that is wary of the militaryapplications that the technology transfer might provide to theSoviet Union.andP;  The DOD has a strong voice on the CoordinatingCommittee on Multilateral Export Controls (COCOM), which iscomposed of most NATO member nations and controls the export ofstrategic technologies, and continues to object to certaintechnology transfers including fiber optics telecommunications.andO;The formation of a single European market in 1992 and the end ofthe cold war may dilute the DOD's efforts to withhold technologyin the near future.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of DefenseTechnology TransferTelecommunicationsSoviet UnionUnited StatesFiber OpticsTransborder Data FlowPolitical IssuesTelephone CompaniesExportSingle European Market.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>